19 PART II. CLARIFY LANGUAGE TO PRECLUDE IMPRISONMENT FOR
20 NONPAYMENT OF FINES AND FEES WHEN ACTIVE SENTENCE IMPOSED
21 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 15A-1364(a) reads as rewritten:
22 "(a) Response to Default. – When a defendant who has been required to pay a fine or costs
23 or both defaults in payment or in any installment, the court, upon the motion of the prosecutor or
24 upon its own motion, may require the defendant to appear and show cause why he should not be
25 imprisoned or may rely upon a conditional show cause order entered under G.S. 15A-1362(c).
26 When making that determination, the court shall consider at a minimum the following factors:
27 (1) The defendant's monthly income in relation to the relevant federal poverty
28 guidelines for the defendant's household size.
29 (2) Whether the defendant receives public assistance, including, but not limited
30 to, food assistance, Medicaid, Social Security Insurance, and Temporary
31 Assistance for Needy Families.
32 (3) The defendant's living arrangements and ability to afford or otherwise procure
33 housing.
34 (4) Whether the defendant resides in a mental health or substance abuse treatment
35 facility.
36 (5) Any limits on the defendant's ability to secure employment, including, but not
37 limited to, lack of access to transportation, limitations upon the defendant's
38 driving privileges, availability of child care for dependents, and any other
39 relevant factors.
40 If the defendant fails to appear, an order for his arrest may be issued. This subsection shall
41 not apply to a defendant who has received an active sentence in the same case in which the
42 defendant has defaulted on the payment of a fine or costs."
43 SECTION 2.(b) G.S. 15A-1365 reads as rewritten:
44 "§ 15A-1365. Judgment for fines docketed; lien and execution.
45 When a defendant has defaulted in payment of a fine or costs, the judge may order that the
46 judgment be docketed. Upon being docketed, the judgment becomes a lien on the real estate of
47 the defendant in the same manner as do judgments in civil actions. Executions on docketed
48 judgments may be stayed only when an appeal is taken and security is given as required in civil
49 cases. If the judgment is affirmed on appeal to the appellate division, the clerk of the superior
50 court, on receipt of the certificate from the appellate division, must issue execution on the
51 judgment. The clerk may not issue an execution, however, if the fine or costs were imposed for
Page 4 House Bill 722-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 an offense other than trafficking in controlled substances or conspiring to traffic in controlled
2 substances under G.S. 90-95(h) and (i), respectively, and the defendant elects to serve the
3 suspended sentence, if any, or serve a term of 30 days, if no suspended sentence was imposed.is
4 serving an active sentence."
