6 PART III. MODIFY THE LAWS GOVERNING THE REVOCATION OF DRIVERS
7 LICENSES FOR FAILURE TO PAY FINE, PENALTY, OR COSTS
8 SECTION 3.(a) G.S. 20-24.1 is repealed.
9 SECTION 3.(b) G.S. 20-24.2 is repealed.
10 SECTION 3.(c) Article 2 of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
11 a new section to read:
12 "§ 20-24.3. Prohibition on revocation issued solely for failure to appear or pay fine, penalty,
13 or costs.
14 Notwithstanding any other provision of law, the Division shall not revoke the drivers license
15 of a person charged with an infraction, misdemeanor, or felony if the revocation is solely for one
16 or both of the following reasons:
17 (1) The person failed to appear, after being notified to do so, when the case was
18 called for a trial or hearing.
19 (2) The person failed to pay a fine, penalty, or court costs ordered by the court."
20 SECTION 3.(d) G.S. 15A-1116(a) reads as rewritten:
21 "(a) Use of Contempt or Fine Collection Procedures: Notification of DMV. – If the person
22 does not comply with a sanction ordered by the court, the court may proceed in accordance with
23 Chapter 5A of the General Statutes. If the person fails to pay a penalty or costs, the court may
24 proceed in accordance with Article 84 of this Chapter. If the infraction is a motor vehicle
25 infraction, the court must report a failure to pay the applicable penalty and costs to the Division
26 of Motor Vehicles as specified in G.S. 20-24.2."
27 SECTION 3.(e) G.S. 20-13.2(e) reads as rewritten:
28 "(e) Before the Division restores a driver's license that has been suspended or revoked
29 under any provision of this Article, other than G.S. 20-24.1, the person seeking to have his
30 driver's license restored shall submit to the Division proof that he has notified his insurance agent
31 or company of his seeking the restoration and that he is financially responsible. Proof of financial
32 responsibility shall be in one of the following forms:
33 …
34 The preceding provisions of this subsection do not apply to applicants who do not own
35 currently registered motor vehicles and who do not operate nonfleet private passenger motor
36 vehicles that are owned by other persons and that are not insured under commercial motor vehicle
37 liability insurance policies. In such cases, the applicant shall sign a written certificate to that
38 effect. Such certificate shall be furnished by the Division and may be incorporated into the
39 restoration application form. Any material misrepresentation made by such person on such
40 certificate shall be grounds for suspension of that person's license for a period of 90 days.
41 For the purposes of this subsection, the term "nonfleet private passenger motor vehicle" has
42 the definition ascribed to it in Article 40 of General Statute Chapter 58.
43 The Commissioner may require that certificates required by this subsection be on a form
44 approved by the Commissioner. The financial responsibility required by this subsection shall be
45 kept in effect for not less than three years after the date that the license is restored. Failure to
46 maintain financial responsibility as required by this subsection shall be grounds for suspending
47 the restored driver's license for a period of thirty (30) days. Nothing in this subsection precludes
48 any person from showing proof of financial responsibility in any other manner authorized by
49 Articles 9A and 13 of this Chapter."
50 SECTION 3.(f) G.S. 20-19(k) reads as rewritten:
